1) Effective final:

In Java, effectively final refers to a local variable or parameter that is never assigned a new value after its initial
assignment — even though it's not explicitly declared with the final keyword.

Introduced in Java 8, it allows lambdas and anonymous inner classes to capture local variables without requiring the final
keyword boilerplate — as long as the variable is never reassigned.


Assigned once, never changed
Declared and assigned separately (once)

Lambdas and anonymous classes capture a copy of the local variable. If the variable could change after capture,
the copy would be stale — leading to inconsistency. Enforcing (effective) finality avoids this.

// Explicitly final (old style)
final String name = "Alice";
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println(name); // OK

// Effectively final (Java 8+) — no 'final' keyword, but never reassigned
String name = "Alice";
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println(name); // Also OK

// NOT effectively final — reassignment breaks it
String name = "Alice";
name = "Bob"; // reassigned!
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println(name); // Compile error



// Common pitfall in loops
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    // 'i' is NOT effectively final — it's modified each iteration
    new Thread(() -> System.out.println(i)).start(); // Compile error
}


// Fix: capture in a local effectively final variable
for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    int index = i; // effectively final
    new Thread(() -> System.out.println(index)).start(); // OK
}
